{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d47da30e-b00d-4303-a084-dd5872d1c0bb","content":"On macOS, crash reports are generated automatically by the system. Look here:\n\n**Crash Reports (text-based, always generated):**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. You can also view them in **Console.app → Crash Reports**.\n\n**Core Dumps (binary, disabled by default):**\n```\n/cores/core.<pid>\n```\nTo enable core dumps *before* reproducing the crash:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is usually sufficient — it contains the exception type, faulting thread, and full stack backtrace with symbol names (if available).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"485954ff-5e48-4907-b91a-bf327059dafd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to find crash dumps or crash reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` is not available. This is a knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nOn macOS, when an application crashes, the system generates crash reports automatically. Here's what they need to know:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports** are stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user apps) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-wide).\n2. They can also use **Console.app** to view crash logs.\n\n\n3. For core dumps specifically, macOS stores them in `/cores/` but they're disabled by default—enabling them requires running `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching the app to allow the system to capture the full memory dump.","outputTokens":424,"requestId":"502F:3C05D0:26D622:305C6D:69F55451"},"id":"f5ff8543-2de2-474e-a04f-8483c1e6a4fe","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:33:15.785Z","parentId":"918104dc-5afc-4cff-a36c-7f952ab962fb"}
